sect1.para:
Psychologists must tune into aspects of diversity during the assessment process and throughout therapy. Identity factors are often social determinants of health, and according to the American Psychological Association (
         2005
      ), best practices in evidence-based assessment and therapy should incorporate identity. Addressing diversity factors is a critical element in the biopsychosocial approach. Additionally, psychologists must demonstrate cultural humility and competency throughout the patient-therapist relationship. Psychologists follow ethical principles
         principles
       and a code of conduct (APA, 
         2017
      ). Specifically, the principles of justice and respect for people’s rights and dignity encompass our duty to address how our clients’ identities, lived experiences, and overall health factor into the care we provide and how we deliver our care. Exploring diversity factors contributes to obtaining the most comprehensive assessment and optimizes rapport, which we know is the number one predictor of a successful therapeutic outcome (Norcross & Lambert, 
         2018
      ). Using the case examples from above and integration
         integration
      of Hays’ (
         2016
      ) ADDRESSING framework, we reflect on ways attention to identity and related intersecting factors can assist in the way psychologists establish rapport and relationships, formulate impressions, recommend treatments, and influence outcomes. We also specifically address these factors per the above case vignettes.

sect2.para:
Substantial literature has demonstrated that transgender and gender-diverse youth and adolescents face significant health disparities due to bullying, emotional distress, and substance use (Eisenberg et al.,
            2020
         ). Furthermore, researchers found that these factors contribute to a heightened risk of chronic diseases and educational/financial disparities in adulthood as a result of untreated injury and illness-related concerns or behaviors (Eisenberg et al., 
            2020
         ).
